    {
      "id": 1926,
      "sender_id": 316,
      "content": "<p>Hi, building on Gan W.'s question — for solvers that need to do <br>\nnon-trivial counterexample search, the following packages would <br>\nbe valuable:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>z3-solver: SMT-based search for finite magmas satisfying Eq1 <br>\n  but violating Eq2. ETP itself uses Z3 (generate_z3_counterexample <br>\n  in teorth/equational_theories). Most direct path to FALSE <br>\n  certificates beyond brute-force enumeration.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>networkx: graph operations on the implication poset. The ETP <br>\n  graph has ~22M edges and reasoning about ancestry/transitive <br>\n  closure is natural in this representation.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>pysat (alternative): if z3-solver is rejected for size or <br>\n  fairness reasons, pure-Python SAT.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>For all three, deterministic seeding is straightforward and the <br>\noutput is a finite witness that the Lean judge can verify <br>\nindependently. Reproducibility is preserved.</p>\n<p>Versions I'd target: z3-solver==4.13.0, networkx==3.3, pysat==1.8.dev1.</p>\n<p>If the team has fairness concerns about z3 specifically (some <br>\nparticipants having local Z3 expertise), a documented allowlist <br>\nof which Z3 APIs are permitted would address that without <br>\nremoving the tool entirely.</p>",
      "recipient_id": 43,
      "timestamp": 1778163021,
      "client": "ZulipFlutter",
